<paragraph id="D137642CFFF9AC03479DFA51FAD5FA66" blockId="3.[136,1452,1394,1564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">
The new Brazilian species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="16881FAFFFF9AC034549FA50FAEFFA5A" authority="A. M. Scott &amp; Gronblad (1957: 30)" authorityName="A. M. Scott &amp; Gronblad" authorityPageNumber="30" authorityYear="1957" box="[617,1338,1394,1421]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Xanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="3" pageNumber="231" phylum="Charophyta" rank="variety" species="concinnum" variety="floridense">
<emphasis id="E3FCB83EFFF9AC034549FA50FCD0FA5A" box="[617,773,1395,1420]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">X. concinnum</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis id="E3FCB83EFFF9AC03441FFA51FC7AFA5A" box="[831,943,1394,1420]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">floridense</emphasis>
A.M. 
<bibRefCitation id="B51919DDFFF9AC0344CCFA51FAEFFA5A" author="Scott, A. M. &amp; Gronblad, R." box="[1004,1338,1394,1421]" pageId="3" pageNumber="231" pagination="1 - 62" refId="ref9413" refString="Scott, A. M. &amp; Gronblad, R. (1957) New and interesting desmids from the southeastern United States. Acta Societatis Scientiarum Fennica 2 (8): 1 - 62." type="journal article" year="1957">Scott &amp; Grönblad (1957: 30)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in frontal view, but it differs by having a short spine at each angle of semicells, which are oblong in apical view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D137642CFFF9AC03479DFA99FED8F9CA" blockId="3.[136,1452,1394,1564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">
Analyzing the geographical distribution of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="16881FAFFFF9AC034434FA99FC0AFA02" authorityName="Compere" authorityYear="1977" box="[788,991,1466,1492]" class="Conjugatophyceae" family="Desmidiaceae" genus="Bourrellyodesmus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygnematales" pageId="3" pageNumber="231" phylum="Charophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E3FCB83EFFF9AC034434FA99FC0AFA02" box="[788,991,1466,1492]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">Bourrellyodesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we noticed that almost all taxa are from tropical areas, and 
<collectingCountry id="A99F24BCFFF9AC03467AFAFDFE4BFA2E" box="[346,414,1502,1528]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="231">Brazil</collectingCountry>
could be an important center of diversity of the genus, with five species currently reported in the country.
</paragraph>
